YouTube Feed: Flow 2. Using Layer Cake Eye Gaze Pattern

By Shawn Graven

This page includes many aspects of the Layer Cake Eye Gaze Pattern. This page in YouTube includes the following:

       Headings

o   h2 (#title-container > h2) shows the author of the video

o   h3 (#title-wrapper > h3) shows the title of the video

       Subheadings (#description-text) in the form of descriptions

       Images that animate on hover (#dismissable > ytd-thumbnail) giving a preview of the video.

       Links

o   Author: (#title-container > h2) Allowing the user to visit the authors home page where they can find all their videos.

o   Video: (#grid-container) Allowing the user to watch the video. The entire field for the video will link to the video making it easy to navigate the site.

       Many horizontal lines

o   Theoretically an infinitely long page as it will load more videos as you scroll down. Creating limitless opportunity for the user to watch something. Given that the user does not get board before that.

       Bold and italics is not used on this site; however, it is possible for authors to use bold font in the description although, this is not used by many people.

People will tend to focus on the headers and the image for multiple reasons making this a Layer Cake Eye Gaze Pattern. The image gives vital information in the form of a preview of what the video will look like. The headers provide details about what the video is about. For example, a title for a lets play may include the game name, episode and season number, what they are doing or something exciting that happened, and sometimes the phrase lets play. This allows the user to identify the game, the number of episodes prior to the video as well as seasons, and the interesting information can make the user click the video. Because most people like images instead of long text and descriptions, the user will tend to look at the image then the title and if it interests them they will either look at the description, click on the video link, or add it to the Watch later list. In fact, people like images so much that the standard flow is a grid of images and the title.
